frameDefinitions: An Item is in a state of wetness with the possibility of the wetting Liquid being mentioned, along with the Degree of wetness. '
The frame represents the result state of the Entity after event represented by the Undergo_change frame.
A Location is filled or covered with the Theme.
An Agent, by virtue of strength or forcefulness, controls, rules, or strongly influences some Patient in some Situation.
An Agent temporarily places a Theme into a Substance, often with the intention to remove it later.

This frame involves a static (primarily spatial) relationship between a Location and a Theme, in which the Theme is located in many or all subregions of the Location, and is thus construable as covering it.
frameExamples: The mop is <t>drenched</t> with water from last night's rain.
The waters of the bay <t>teemed</t> with fish.
The fireballing righthander looked poised to <t>dominate</t> the Yankees yet again, striking out seven straight batters during one stretch
She <t>dunked</t> her sandwich into some tomato soup.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Item</fen> takes up the <fen>Liquid</fen> through its pores.
The <fen>Liquid</fen> is a fluid or gas that permeates the <fen>Item</fen>.  It most frequently occurs in a PP Complement headed by with.
The <fen>Theme</fen> covers or fills the <fen>Location</fen>.  This role most frequently occurs in a PP Complement headed by with or in.
<fen>Location</fen> is the object or area that the <fen>Theme</fen> fills or covers.  This frame element generally occurs as the External Argument.
The period of time during which the the Abounding_with event occurs.
The <fen>Agent</fen> controls the Patient by being forceful and possibly aggressive.
The <fen>Patient</fen> is trying to gain control of a situation, but ends up being subject to the control and influence of the <fen>Agent</fen>.
The time when the domination takes place.
The place where the domination occurs.
The <fen>Theme</fen> temporarily goes partially or completely into the Substance.
The <fen>Substance</fen> is the fluid into which the <fen>Theme</fen> is placed. This may be metonymically represented by the container of the fluid.
The location in time when the dunking occurs.

The <fen>Theme</fen> in this frame is the object which is described as standing in some spatial relation to a particular <fen>Location</fen>.  <fen>Theme</fen> typically occurs as the External Argument or, with passives, as a PP Complement headed by 'with' or 'by'.
<fen>Location</fen> is the entity or area with respect to which the <fen>Theme</fen>'s spatial arrangement is described.  This frame element generally occurs as an NP Object.
The time at which the <fen>Theme</fen> occupies the <fen>Location</fen>.
listRoleExamples: The mop was drenched <fex> with water</fex>.
The waters of the bay teemed <fex>with fish</fex>.
<fex>The walls</fex> crawled with nanite surveillance probes.
Their role models might have dominated women <fex>in the past</fex>; they may not have understood the concept of equality.
Women tend to dominatemen <fex>at home and at Church</fex>.
<fex>She</fex> dunked her sandwich into some tomato soup.
She dunked <fex>her sandwich</fex> into some tomato soup.
She dunked her sandwich <fex>into some tomato soup</fex>.
